From #415 this adds universal base64 encoding via
```
module {
   value:base64 = '<encoded>'
}
```

@ultrabug if you are happy with this concept I'll update this PR with some documentation

This pull request was inspired by a comment in https://github.com/banga/powerline-shell/pull/319

Here I have created a generic segment called "inline" which handles segments defined as a configuration in the config file. You can have multiples using different commands. The configuration here was provided in the comment from the pull request mentioned above and is not my layout.

Sample configuration in the segments array:

   {
            "type": "stdout",
            "options":{"command": ["hostname", "-f"]}
    }

FileSystem (parent class) has mkdir defined as:

def mkdir(self, path, parents=True, raise_if_exists=False):
   ...

@nramirezuy noticed that "|" is not in RFC3986: https://github.com/scrapy/scrapy/issues/508#issuecomment-50087286. I've checked the RFC and updated code to use constants from this RFC:
- "|" is removed;
- "[" and "]" are added.

In partial fulfillment of https://jira.numenta.com/browse/RES-112

Fixes #2730 (a sub-issue of #2271). 

@BoltzmannBrain Ready for review

The API has started returning metadata, e.g.

    {u'mid': u'/m/020bg'}

and has added "painter" as a mention of Michelangelo.

str is not bytes under python3, if dns config is a list, will cause asyncdns.py failed:

asyncdns.py:
..........

    def handle_event(self, sock, fd, event):
        if sock != self._sock:
            return
        if event & eventloop.POLL_ERR:
       ...........
        else:
            data, addr = sock.recvfrom(1024)
            if addr[0] not in self._servers:
                logging.warn('received a packet other than our dns')
                return
            self._handle_data(data)

cc @dsblank @whositwhatnow 

> Are the Assignments list showing up? No, then they might need to edit nbgrader_config.py. I have seen that file: with the wrong name, typos (case, missing quotes).

@dsblank you left this comment in #541. Can you give me a more specific example of what went wrong? Was the class name wrong or something? Do you have the error that it printed out? I'm happy to update this PR with more specifics about this suggestion, I just am not entirely sure what would specifically be most helpful to include.

Consider:

```python
class M(Model):

    f = StringType()

    @serializable
    def s(self):
        return 'foo'
```

Since `M.f == M._fields['f']`, I would expect `M.s == M._serializables['s']` to be true as well.

But accessing `M.s` currently results in `M.s()` to be evaluated as if it were a classmethod. I suspect this is not by design. Does anyone else see a reason why this should be so?

@nebulaV After [this commit](https://github.com/tensorlayer/tensorlayer/commit/025e874aa82058a54a131292f172ac00edb5f239#diff-dffe1d7a32e99bc0c815dedb99c8a90e), all RNN layers with `n_layer` can't work when `n_layer > 1` .

I updated the test code for `recurrent.py` here [test_layers_recurrent.py](https://github.com/tensorlayer/tensorlayer/blob/master/tests/test_layers_recurrent.py), could you please fix this bug? The robot will help to check the bugs, or you can run the test script locally. 

Many thanks.
